bug.short_desc: second list which is bound to another list with a controller shows wrong info

long_desc.thetext:
Hello Martin I found another bug which I tried to solve first but I couldn't solve by myself so could you please help.
The problem occurs when you bind two qx.ui.form.List widgets by a controller just like on the demopage: demobrowser.demo.data.ListController.
When you select multiple items on the first list (I took the first three of them) then the third list will show all three of them what's right of course. But when I deselect the first item of the first list the third list will show two items which is also right but one of them is the wrong item!
My third list should look like - Item 1 - Item 2 But that's not happening, it looks like - Item 0(Which I had deselected) - Item 2
I lost my way at the bindings when I was debugging, when stepping over the code I saw that the old model triggered the item which it was bound too just after the new model had applied it's value.
Good luck.
Created attachment 902 screenshot of the problem
Thanks for the report. I guess thats something which should be fixed in the selection handling of the controller. I take care of it.

(In reply to comment #2) > Thanks for the report. I guess thats something which should be fixed in the > selection handling of the controller. I take care of it.
You're welcome, thank you for your great work Martin, by the way the new/renewed theme's are very nice.
Fixed the first problem but found another one. Selecting first Item 0, then additionally Item 2 and after that, Item 1 will result in a selection of Item 0, Item 2 and Item 2 (twice)

Finally found a fix for all of the problems. The reason why it went wrong was quite obvious in the end. The single value binding optimizes the change events of the data arrays and only updates the target widgets in case the change event contains the hints that the binding needs to be updated. Unfortunately, the change of the selection was not programmed quite right and manipulated the data directly in the array without firing the proper event. So the single value binding got a change event and the data was not correct which elements have changed so the updated of the target widgets was canceled due to the information that they didn't change, which was not the case.
Using the splice method as the one single change (delete and add together) fixed the problem with the wrang data in the change event and everything was back the way it should have ever been.
